Toggle navigation En français Browse Job Listings FAQ Contact Register Log in Log in Forgot password? Supervisor, Programs &amp; Outreach (Region of Waterloo Library) Baden , ON Description About Us! The Region of Waterloo is a thriving, diverse community committed to fostering opportunities for current and future generations. Home to over 674,000 residents and expected to grow to nearly one million by 2051. Guided by our 2023-2027 Strategic Plan, “Growing with Care,” we focus on equity, inclusion, and sustainability. Our mission is to provide essential services that enhance the quality of life for all residents, while our core values emphasize caring for people and the land we share. Join us and be part of a team dedicated to making a meaningful difference in our community. Dish with One Spoon Wampum:Waterloo Region is part of the Dish with One Spoon wampum, a treaty guiding our commitment to: Recognizing our shared humanity and landTaking only what we needLeaving some for othersKeeping the dish cleanThis agreement underpins our vision, mission, and core values, and reinforces our dedication to meaningful reconciliation and equity. The Role Supervises the development and delivery of programs and outreach for library users of all ages, including promotions and marketing, and related services. Duties/Responsibilities Supervises programming staff, a coordinator, and volunteers assisting with programs. Provides guidance to other library staff as it relates to programs and outreach, and fosters a collaborative/cooperative approach to system-wide programming.Develops new programs to expand reach and appeal of the library. Keeps current with industry trends to generate ideas and ensure programming stays current.Oversees current programming, monitors effectiveness, and recommends/implements improvements. Monitors, assesses, and takes remedial steps to ensure programming is delivered at a high quality across locations.Develops and coordinates annual program schedules, including author visits, special presentations, and regular session programs.Maintains an active outreach and public relations program to develop community support and partnerships. Attends/assigns staff to attend community events (e.g., trade shows, school visits). Represents the library/assigns staff to community projects/events, special committees and task forces, in collaboration with other management staff.Supervises program promotions, including the production of marketing and advertising materials. Consults with other supervisors regarding programs, as necessary. Ensures advertising, promotional materials, and social media activities are completed in a professional and timely manner.Recommends policies and initiatives to promote and support the long-term viability of program provision and library service. Develops partnerships with community organizations, other levels of government, and other library systems to pool resources, resolve programming issues, and build relationships.Monitors to ensure programs stay within budget, and makes recommendations to Manager for increases/changes to budget, and purchases. Monitors condition of program resource material collection and recommends replacement to ensure materials are kept in good condition. Applies for program funding in consultation with Manager.Assesses need for volunteers in program delivery. Follows volunteer policy and procedures to guide individuals to assist with library programs.Maintains knowledge of library procedures and technology through scheduled shifts in library branches.Collaborates with library management team to anticipate and resolve operating issues, develop policies, implement system-wide change, and coordinate staffingrequirements. Participates in meetings at the region-wide level (e.g. early literacy, children and youth).Performs related duties as required. Knowledge, Skills, and Abilities Knowledge of programming principles, trends and technology, learning methods, public library services, effective writing and presentation skills, promotions, marketing, social media, and community partnership, normally acquired through a Master of Library and Information Science degree –OR– a related degree plus directly related library experience.Knowledge of and ability to comply with policies, procedures, collective agreements, and legislation/standards (e.g., privacy, accessibility, duty to report suspected child abuse).Problem solving, creativity, continuous improvement, and organizational skills to plan programs and learning opportunities; integrate new technology into programs; evaluate program performance and review programming trends to recommend/implement service improvements and keep programming current relative to the market; and expand the reach of programs by overseeing promotional, marketing, and social media outreach activities.Communication, leadership, and human relations skills to supervise, train, develop, motivate, and support staff; respond to program inquiries/complaints; foster collaboration with staff and community partners; communicate effectively with groups of all ages, conduct presentations, and provide information and training; and participate as an effective team member.Ability to read correspondence, reports, and data. Ability to write effectively for varied audiences and communication channels (web, print, audio, reports).Computer skills using software such as Microsoft Office, the internet, integrated library software, and virtual library resources and databases.Ability to travel within Waterloo Region.Ability to support and demonstrate the Region’s values. To Apply: Please copy and paste this link into your browser: https://careers.regionofwaterloo.ca/job- invite/1565 The Region of Waterloo is an equal opportunity employer committed to an inclusive, barrier-free recruitment and selection process. The Region of Waterloo invites applications from all qualified individuals. We are strongly committed to employment equity, diversity and inclusion in the workplace and encourage applications from Black, racialized/visible minorities, Indigenous/Aboriginal people, women, persons with disabilities, and 2SLGBTQIA+ persons. The Region of Waterloo is committed to providing accommodations throughout the recruitment process. If you require an accommodation, please notify us and we will work with you to meet your needs. Alternate formats of this document are available upon request. Please contact the Service First Contact Centre at phone number (519) 575-4400, TTY number (519-575-4608) to request an alternate format. Please note: candidates will be provided an update on their application Please check your spam or junk folder occasionally as some candidates have noticed our emails in those folders (Gmail and Hotmail in particular). Compensation $81,718.00 - $102,138.40 per year Closes: 27 September, 2024 Region of Waterloo Library Baden , ON Policies and Terms of Use · jobboard@bcla.bc.ca / BCLA PO BOX 19008, Rocky Point PO, Port Moody, BC V3H 0J1 window.dataLayer = window.dataLayer || [];
